When using the [FormData API][1] to POST files and data, it is important to set the [Content-Type header](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Type) to `undefined`.&lt;sup&gt;[1][1]&lt;/sup&gt;

[1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/41754333/5535245

    var converttoBytes = {
        filesBytes: function (p) {
            var url = &#39;/api/immigration/application/getFileObj/dddd&#39;;
            var config = { headers: { &#39;Content-Type&#39;: undefined } };
            return $http.post(url, p, config);
        }
    }


By default the AngularJS framework uses content type `application/json`. By setting `Content-Type: undefined`, the AngularJS framework omits the content type header allowing the [XHR API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest) to set the content type. When sending a [FormData object][1], the XHR API sets the content type to `multipart/form-data` with the proper boundaries and encoding.

[1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData

For more information, see [MDN Web API Reference - XHR Send method](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest/send)

